Part 3 — Step 1 (Upload Files) detailed specification
Expected file set:
The pipeline expects exactly 8 source feeds, each as a separate .xlsx file. Each feed has a canonical name and is matched to uploaded files by filename (case-insensitive, with normalization for common suffixes such as _v2, _final, dates, and underscores vs. dashes):

risk_register — Risk Register: core risk inventory
risk_library — Risk Library: taxonomy, categories, risk statements
controls — Controls: control inventory
control_assessments — Control Assessments: ratings and effectiveness data
issues — Issues: identified gaps and findings
corrective_action_plans — CAPs: remediation plans
business_units — Business Units: organizational scope
applications — Applications: application inventory

(This list is provisional. Confirm with the project owner before final implementation. Replace any placeholder names with the actual feed names used by the engine.)
Define this list, along with each feed's expected schema (column names and required types), in a separate configuration file (e.g., feed_config.yaml or feed_schemas.py) so it can be modified without changing UI code.
Upload area behavior:

Drag-and-drop area accepting one or more .xlsx files
Click-to-browse alternative (file picker dialog)
Multiple files can be uploaded in a single drag or selection
Uploading additional files adds to the existing list, does not replace it
Each uploaded file shows: filename, size, matched feed name (if matched), and a per-file remove control
Folders cannot be uploaded — display message: "Please upload individual .xlsx files, not folders"
Maximum file size per file: 50 MB (display error if exceeded)
Uploaded files are held client-side until validation passes; they are not transmitted to any backend until then

Primary button states inside Step 1:

Idle (no files): label Upload Files, button disabled
Files uploaded, not yet validated: label Validate Files →, button enabled
Validation in progress: label Validating files…, button disabled
Validation complete with errors: label Re-validate →, button enabled
Validation complete with no errors: Step 1 is marked complete, the step body collapses, and Step 2 reveals automatically


Part 4 — Validation logic and test cases
When the user clicks Validate Files →, run all four validation categories in order. Display all results inline within Step 1, grouped by category. Do not clear uploaded files on validation failure. Allow the user to remove or replace individual files and re-validate without losing state.
Category 1: Missing required feeds
Compare uploaded files against the 8 expected feeds using filename matching (case-insensitive, normalizing common suffixes).
Test cases:

TC1.1: User uploads 0 files → display "All 8 required feeds are missing" with the list of expected feed names
TC1.2: User uploads 1 file matching risk_register → display "7 required feeds missing" with the list of the 7 missing feed names
TC1.3: User uploads 8 files but none match the expected names → display "All 8 required feeds are missing" + 8 unexpected files (see Category 4)
TC1.4: User uploads 7 of 8 correct feeds → display "1 required feed missing: [feed name]"
TC1.5: User uploads all 8 correct feeds → no missing-feed error

Each missing-feed error must include:

The canonical feed name
A brief description of what the feed contains
A clear next step ("Add this feed by uploading a file named [feed_name].xlsx or similar")

Category 2: Duplicate files
Detect three types of duplication. Each is reported separately.
2a — Filename duplicates: same filename uploaded more than once

TC2a.1: User uploads risk_register.xlsx twice → blocking error: "Duplicate filename: risk_register.xlsx was uploaded twice. Remove one copy to proceed."

2b — Content duplicates: different filenames, identical file content (compared by file hash)

TC2b.1: User uploads risk_register.xlsx and risk_register_copy.xlsx with byte-identical content → warning (non-blocking): "Possible duplicate content: risk_register.xlsx and risk_register_copy.xlsx appear to be identical. Confirm which version to use."

2c — Feed identifier duplicates: two files matched to the same expected feed

TC2c.1: User uploads risk_register.xlsx and risk_register_v2.xlsx (both match the risk_register feed) → blocking error: "Two files matched to the Risk Register feed: risk_register.xlsx and risk_register_v2.xlsx. Remove one or rename so only one matches."

Filename duplicates and feed identifier duplicates are blocking errors — Step 1 cannot complete. Content duplicates are warnings — Step 1 can complete but the user is prompted to confirm.
Category 3: Schema issues
For each uploaded file matched to an expected feed, validate the schema against the configuration file.
3a — Missing required columns:

TC3a.1: Risk Register file is missing the RiskID column → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx is missing required column: RiskID. Check the column headers."

3b — Misnamed columns (close match):

TC3b.1: Risk Register file has Risk_ID instead of RiskID → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx has an unexpected column Risk_ID. Did you mean RiskID? Rename the column to match the expected schema."

3c — Wrong data types:

TC3c.1: Risk Register has text values in a column that should be numeric → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx column RiskScore contains non-numeric values in rows [list]. Correct the values or check the column type."

3d — Empty mandatory fields:

TC3d.1: Risk Register has empty cells in the RiskID column (mandatory) → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx has empty values in mandatory column RiskID at rows [list]. Fill in the missing values."

3e — Extra columns (informational, not blocking):

TC3e.1: Risk Register has all required columns plus 2 extra columns → info only: "risk_register.xlsx has 2 extra columns that will be ignored: [list]. This is informational only."

3f — Wrong sheet (multi-sheet workbook):

TC3f.1: Uploaded .xlsx has multiple sheets and the first sheet is not the data sheet → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx contains multiple sheets. Specify which sheet contains the data, or move the data to the first sheet."

Category 4: Invalid file types
4a — Unsupported extensions:

TC4a.1: User uploads .csv → blocking error: "controls.csv is not a supported file type. Convert to .xlsx and re-upload."
TC4a.2: User uploads .xls (older Excel format) → warning: "risk_register.xls is an older Excel format. Save as .xlsx for best compatibility."
TC4a.3: User uploads .pdf → blocking error: "controls.pdf is not a supported file type. Upload .xlsx files only."

4b — Corrupted files:

TC4b.1: User uploads a .xlsx that cannot be opened → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx could not be opened. The file may be corrupted. Re-export from the source system."

4c — Empty files:

TC4c.1: User uploads a .xlsx with 0 rows → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx is empty. Verify the file has content and re-upload."
TC4c.2: User uploads a .xlsx of 0 bytes → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx is empty (0 bytes). The file did not upload correctly. Re-upload."

4d — Password-protected files:

TC4d.1: User uploads an encrypted .xlsx → blocking error: "risk_register.xlsx is password-protected. Remove the password and re-upload."

Combination test cases
The validation must handle multiple simultaneous errors gracefully:

TC-Combo.1: User uploads 5 files: 1 correct, 1 with schema issue, 1 duplicate, 1 invalid type, 1 unmatched filename → display all categories of error simultaneously, grouped by category, with clear separation
TC-Combo.2: User has prior validation errors, removes 1 problematic file, uploads a corrected version, re-validates → only the resolved errors disappear; remaining errors stay visible
TC-Combo.3: User uploads 8 valid files, validates successfully, then drags a 9th file → the 9th file is matched against expected feeds; if it duplicates an existing feed, raise duplicate error; if not, raise unexpected-file warning

Error display conventions

All errors appear inline within Step 1, grouped by category in this order: Missing → Duplicate → Schema → Invalid Type → Combination notes
Each error names the specific file or feed it relates to
Each error provides a clear, actionable next step
Errors auto-dismiss when the underlying issue is resolved (no manual close required)
Blocking errors prevent Step 1 from completing; warnings allow completion but display a confirmation prompt
When validation completes with no errors, the entire error display area collapses cleanly


Part 5 — Steps 2, 3, and 4 (Check, Load, Validate)
Once Step 1 completes successfully, proceed through Steps 2–4 sequentially. Each step appears with its own action button and inline result display.
Step 2 — Check: "Confirms every required source feed is present in the working folder." Action button: Run Check →
Step 3 — Load: "Reads each feed into memory and locks the chosen version so nothing changes underneath the pipeline mid-run." Action button: Run Load →
Step 4 — Validate: "Verifies that every feed has the columns downstream stages need." Action button: Run Validate →
Each step's action button changes label and color across idle → in progress → complete states, consistent with the design system. Step results are displayed inline (pass/fail with details).
Important: With Step 1 now performing upload-time validation (schema, file presence), Steps 2–4 may have overlapping responsibilities with the existing engine logic. Confirm with the project owner whether these steps remain distinct operations (e.g., Check verifies file presence at runtime, Load opens the files in memory, Validate re-verifies columns at the engine level) or whether they should be consolidated. Document the decision in STAGE_PAGE_DESIGN_SPEC.md.
When Step 4 completes successfully, the stage-level Run Pipeline → CTA appears below the stepper, advancing the user to Stage 2.

Part 6 — State management

Uploaded files persist across navigation away from Stage 1 and back, within the same session
Validation results persist until the user uploads new files or removes existing ones
The stepper remembers which steps have been completed and which is currently active, and reflects this when the user returns to Stage 1
Sub-tab selection ("Classic" or "New (Beta)") persists within the session


Part 7 — Run initialization (backend behavior)
When the user begins Stage 1 by uploading their first file (in either tab) or otherwise starting an action, a new processing session is created on the backend, identified by username and timestamp. This is not exposed prominently in the UI but should appear in the existing "Run Timeline" section as a small label (e.g., "Run started: 10:42 AM by [username]").
This is a backend specification, not a UI feature. The UI should not surface session creation as a user-visible action.

